th the zest that characterizes Marinella’s other works, this poem is a great example of a woman engaging critically with a quintessentially masculine form and subject matter, writing in a genre in which the work of women poets was typically shunned.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aItalian poetryy12th century. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  aepic poetry, civilization, byzantium, empire, rise and fall, war, courage, translation, fourth crusade, conquest, conversion, religion, christianity, catholicism, invasion, military, expansion, islam, romance, chivalry, gender, masculinity, women writers, female author, literature, italy, europe, genre, battle, heroism, conflict, territory.1 aJr., Albert Rabil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStampino, Maria Galli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022650547340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226505497423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226505497/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles